docs.abstract: The administration plans to issue licenses allowing some American companies to sell nonsensitive products to Huawei, despite its placement on a U.S. blacklist.
docs.snippet: The administration plans to issue licenses allowing some American companies to sell nonsensitive products to Huawei, despite its placement on a U.S. blacklist.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration plans to soon issue licenses allowing some American companies to supply nonsensitive goods to the Chinese telecom giant Huawei, according to people familiar with the matter, a step that could cool tensions between the United States and China as trade talks resume this week.

headline.main: Trump Green-Lights Some Sales to Huawei
headline.print_headline: Trump Expected to Allow Limited Sales to Huawei

docs.abstract: The tariff fight has added to Chinese shoppers’ grocery bills. How is the government coping? By tapping its gigantic stockpile of emergency meat.
docs.snippet: The tariff fight has added to Chinese shoppers’ grocery bills. How is the government coping? By tapping its gigantic stockpile of emergency meat.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — When supplies of China’s favorite meat run low, Beijing calls upon its strategic pork reserve, a name that brings to mind vast piles of sausages, bacon and spareribs housed in secret underground vaults across the country.

headline.main: Swine Fever? Trade War? China Turns to Strategic Pork Reserve
headline.print_headline: Stockpiling Hogs for a Rainy Day

docs.abstract: The utility, criticized for a botched execution of blackouts two weeks ago, said it was acting to prevent wildfires caused by its equipment.
docs.snippet: The utility, criticized for a botched execution of blackouts two weeks ago, said it was acting to prevent wildfires caused by its equipment.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two weeks after a vast power shut-off that it acknowledged it had mishandled, California’s largest utility began a new round of electricity cuts Wednesday to reduce hazards from power lines and towers in the face of a new wildfire threat.

headline.main: PG&E Begins Power Shut-Off to 179,000 California Customers
headline.print_headline: Utility Again Cuts Power  To Meet Wildfire Threat

docs.abstract: The head of California’s biggest utility, under fire over the company’s handling of a pre-emptive power shut-off, faced scrutiny from state regulators.
docs.snippet: The head of California’s biggest utility, under fire over the company’s handling of a pre-emptive power shut-off, faced scrutiny from state regulators.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Executives of California’s largest power company received withering criticism from state regulators Friday over a pre-emptive blackout that left millions without power, some for days.

headline.main: ‘This Is Not Hard’: PG&E Gets an Earful Over Its Blackout
headline.print_headline: PG&E Chief In Hot Seat  Over Outage

docs.abstract: Companies have binged on share buybacks in recent years, pumping up prices, but their appetite could wane as economic uncertainty rises.
docs.snippet: Companies have binged on share buybacks in recent years, pumping up prices, but their appetite could wane as economic uncertainty rises.
docs.lead_paragraph: American companies spent more than $800 billion on their own shares last year, taking a windfall from deep corporate tax cuts to try to bolster their share prices and improve the look of their quarterly earnings reports.

headline.main: C.E.O.s Are Anxious About the Economy. That’s Bad for Stocks.
headline.print_headline: As C.E.O.s Fret, Stock Buybacks Slow
